claims:
Claims 1. A method for wireless communication, comprising: using a routing table for multiple secure elements, wherein the routing table assigns a preferred secure element for a transaction type; selecting a first secure element for a transaction based on the routing table; and updating the routing table based on a received command to use a second secure element to complete the transaction. 2. The method of claim 1, wherein selecting the first secure element for the transaction comprises: determining a transaction type of the transaction; and using the routing table to determine that the first secure element is the preferred secure element for the transaction type. 3. The method of claim 1, wherein updating the routing table comprises: requesting confirmation from a user to use the first secure element for the transaction; receiving the command to use the second secure element to complete the transaction instead of the first secure element; and assigning the second secure element as the preferred secure element for the transaction type in the routing table. 4. The method of claim 1, further comprising dynamically selecting the second secure element for a subsequent transaction with a same transaction type based on the updated routing table. 5. The method of claim 1, further comprising creating the routing table based on user preferences for transaction types provided at initiation of the multiple secure elements. 6. The method of claim 1, wherein transaction types of the routing table are organized in one or more categories. 7. The method of claim 6, wherein the one or more categories comprise at least one of a purchase category and an institution category. 8. The method of claim 1, wherein the routing table is sent to a near- field communication (NFC) controller. 9. The method of claim 8, wherein a payment system of the NFC controller uses the routing table to determine which secure element to select for a particular transaction. 10. An electronic device for wireless communication, comprising: a processor; memory in electronic communication with the processor; and instructions stored in the memory, the instructions being executable by the processor to: use a routing table for multiple secure elements, wherein the routing table assigns a preferred secure element for a transaction type; select a first secure element for a transaction based on the routing table; and update the routing table based on a received command to use a second secure element to complete the transaction. 11. The electronic device of claim 10, wherein the instructions executable to select the first secure element for the transaction comprise instructions executable to: determine a transaction type of the transaction; and use the routing table to determine that the first secure element is the preferred secure element for the transaction type. 12. The electronic device of claim 10, wherein the instructions executable to update the routing table comprise instructions executable to: request confirmation from a user to use the first secure element for the transaction; 

 receive the command to use the second secure element to complete the transaction instead of the first secure element; and assign the second secure element as the preferred secure element for the transaction type in the routing table. 13. The electronic device of claim 10, further comprising instructions executable to dynamically select the second secure element for a subsequent transaction with a same transaction type based on the updated routing table. 14. The electronic device of claim 10, further comprising instructions executable to create the routing table based on user preferences for transaction types provided at initiation of the multiple secure elements. 15. The electronic device of claim 10, wherein transaction types of the routing table are organized in one or more categories. 16. The electronic device of claim 10, wherein the routing table is sent to a near-field communication (NFC) controller. 17. A computer-program product for wireless communication, comprising a non- transitory tangible computer-readable medium having instructions thereon, the instructions comprising: code for causing an electronic device to use a routing table for multiple secure elements, wherein the routing table assigns a preferred secure element for a transaction type; code for causing the electronic device to select a first secure element for a transaction based on the routing table; and code for causing the electronic device to update the routing table based on a received command to use a second secure element to complete the transaction. 18. The computer-program product of claim 17, wherein the code for causing the electronic device to select the first secure element for the transaction comprises: code for causing the electronic device to determine a transaction type of the transaction; and code for causing the electronic device to use the routing table to determine that the first secure element is the preferred secure element for the transaction type. 19. The computer-program product of claim 17, wherein the code for causing the electronic device to update the routing table comprises: code for causing the electronic device to request confirmation from a user to use the first secure element for the transaction; code for causing the electronic device to receive the command to use the second secure element to complete the transaction instead of the first secure element; and code for causing the electronic device to assign the second secure element as the preferred secure element for the transaction type in the routing table. 20. The computer-program product of claim 17, further comprising code for causing the electronic device to dynamically select the second secure element for a subsequent transaction with a same transaction type based on the updated routing table. 21. The computer-program product of claim 17, further comprising code for causing the electronic device to create the routing table based on user preferences for transaction types provided at initiation of the multiple secure elements. 22. The computer-program product of claim 17, wherein transaction types of the routing table are organized in one or more categories. 23. The computer-program product of claim 17, wherein the routing table is sent to a near-field communication (NFC) controller. 24. An apparatus for wireless communication, comprising: 

